    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <!-- transcription goes here -->
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Domitia">Domitia</name> <persName><g type="Gaiae"/></persName> <expan><abbr>l</abbr><ex>iberta</ex></expan> <name type="cognomen" key="Plecusa">Plecusa</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/>monumentum fecit 
                    <lb n="3"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Caius"><expan><abbr>C</abbr><ex>aio</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Popillius">Popillio</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Anthus">Antho</name></persName>,
                    <lb n="4"/>unguentario, viro suo, 
                    <lb n="5"/>cum quo vix<hi rend="tall">i</hi>t annos <num value="35">XXX<hi rend="superscript">V</hi></num>,
                    <lb n="6"/>et <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Caius"><expan><abbr>C</abbr><ex>aius</ex></expan></name> <name type="genitilicum" key="Popillius">Popillius</name> <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Caius"><expan><abbr>C<am>C</am></abbr><ex>aiorum</ex></expan></name></persName>
                       <expan><abbr>l</abbr><ex>ibertus</ex></expan> <name type="cognomen" key="Hermeros"><expan><abbr>Hermer</abbr><ex>os</ex></expan></name></persName>, 
                    <lb n="7"/> libertus.
                </ab>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p> Remains of guiding lines evident. There are interpuncts after each word except after the last word in each line.
                    The interpuncts in lines 2, 3 and 5 (with the exception of the mark between
                    annos and XXXV) are shaped like ivy leaves. Wilson argues that the space under the inscription was meant for
                    two-three more lines of text (Wilson, 1910, no. 35) and thus the inscription is
                    unfinished. </p>
            </div>

            <div type="translation">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p>"Domitia Plecusa, the freedwoman of Gaia (a woman) makes this monument for Gaius
                    Popillius Anthus, the oil-seller, her husband with whom she lived for thirty
                    five years, and Gaius Popillius Hermeros, the freedman of Gaius and Gaius, the
                    freedman."</p>
            </div>

